Title:
Cytoskeletal Distributed Intelligence: A Geometrically-Constrained Framework for Safe, Real-Time Embodied Reasoning

Candidate: Ouadi Maakoul
Department: Robotics & Autonomous Systems
Date: March 2026

---

1. 🌌 Abstract

The integration of Vision-Language-Action (VLA) foundation models into robotics promises unprecedented generalization, yet these systems remain black-boxes with no formal guarantees of stability or safety. Conversely, classical control theory provides rigorous certificates but cannot leverage semantic understanding. This thesis resolves this dichotomy through a unified mathematical framework that binds semantic reasoning to Lyapunov stability.

We introduce the Cytoskeletal Distributed Intelligence Architecture (CDIA) , where robotic cognition is modeled as a switching dynamical system on a time-varying graph. Inspired by biological cytoskeletons, information pathways polymerize and depolymerize based on task demand, enabling sparse computation without sacrificing representational power. The architecture is built upon three foundational pillars:

1. Geometric Perception: SE(3)-equivariant scene graph construction using Tensor Field Networks, ensuring that all internal representations respect the physical symmetries of the world.
2. Dynamic Graph Cognition: A neural ODE governing both node states and graph topology, with proven contraction bounds that guarantee global stability despite switching.
3. Safety-Critical Control: A Control Barrier Function (CBF) shield that projects foundation model outputs onto the set of safe actions, providing hard guarantees of forward invariance.

Core Contribution: This thesis provides the first formal proof that a learning-based, modular cognitive architecture can maintain contraction (exponential convergence to desired trajectories) and safety (constraint satisfaction) under arbitrary task-driven reconfiguration. We validate CDIA on long-horizon manipulation tasks, demonstrating order-of-magnitude improvements in sample efficiency and zero-shot generalization to novel object poses.

