2. 🎯 Problem Statement

2.1 The Safety-Generalization Dichotomy

Contemporary robotics faces a fundamental tension:

Paradigm Strengths Weaknesses
Classical Control (MPC, LQR, CBF) Formal safety/stability proofs, real-time capable No semantic understanding, poor generalization
Foundation Models (RT-2, OpenVLA, Diffusion Policy) Rich semantic grounding, few-shot generalization Black-box, no certificates, computationally intractable
Geometric DL (SE(3)-Transformers) Exploits symmetry, data-efficient Typically static, not integrated with control

The Gap: No existing framework simultaneously provides:

· Formal certificates (Lyapunov stability, barrier functions)
· Semantic reasoning (language grounding, task composition)
· Real-time computation (O(N) instead of O(N²))
· Symmetry awareness (equivariance to rotations/translations)

2.2 The Computational Bottleneck

Transformer-based policies scale quadratically with context length. For a 7-DoF arm operating at 1kHz, even a single forward pass through a 100M-parameter model is infeasible on edge hardware. Yet biological brains achieve remarkable efficiency through sparse, dynamic connectivity—only 1-2% of neurons are active at any moment.

2.3 Research Questions

Primary: Can we formulate robotic cognition as a switching dynamical system on a time-varying graph such that:

· (RQ1) The system is contracting (exponentially stable) despite arbitrary topology changes?
· (RQ2) Safety constraints are guaranteed via barrier functions that interact with learned components?
· (RQ3) The resulting architecture achieves real-time inference (O(N)) on edge hardware?

Secondary: Does imposing SE(3)-equivariance throughout the pipeline (perception → cognition → action) enable zero-shot generalization to novel object configurations?

