5. 🔬 Experimental Methodology

5.1 Research Phases & Hypotheses

Phase I: Theory (Months 1-15)

· H1: The cytoskeletal switching law maintains contraction if the graph's algebraic connectivity remains bounded below.
· H2: Robust CBFs can guarantee safety with learned uncertainty bounds.

Phase II: Simulation (Months 16-30)

· H3: CDIA achieves 10x better sample efficiency than dense transformers on long-horizon tasks.
· H4: SE(3)-equivariance enables zero-shot generalization to novel object poses.

Phase III: Real World (Months 31-42)

· H5: The full system runs at 100Hz on Jetson Orin with <5ms latency.
· H6: Safety violations are zero across 1000 real-world trials.

5.2 Tasks & Datasets

Task Description Metrics Dataset Source
T1: Table Cleaning Pick 5 objects, place in bin. Random poses. Success rate, time, safety violations Open X-Embodiment + Custom
T2: Dynamic Obstacle Reach target while human waves obstacle Min distance to obstacle, success Custom
T3: Novel Objects 20 unseen objects, language commands Generalization score YCB + Custom scans
T4: Tool Use "Use hammer to pound nail" Success, efficiency RoboTurk + Custom

5.3 Ablation Studies

We compare:

1. CDIA-Full: Complete architecture
2. CDIA-Static: Graph topology fixed (no cytoskeleton)
3. CDIA-NoCBF: Remove safety filter
4. CDIA-Euclidean: Replace SE(3) features with Euclidean
5. Baseline-RT2: Fine-tuned OpenVLA
6. Baseline-MPC: Model-predictive control with vision

5.4 Real-World Platform

· Robot: Franka Emika Panda (7-DoF)
· Sensors: Intel RealSense D455 (x2)
· Compute: NVIDIA Jetson Orin (edge) + RTX 4090 workstation (training)
· Safety: Emergency stop + external motion capture for ground truth

